# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: style-transfer-cv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:style-transfer-cv/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:style-transfer-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/feature-extraction] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A **generative adversarial network** (**GAN**) is a class of machine learning frameworks and a prominent framework for approaching generative artificial intelligence.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The concept was initially developed by Ian Goodfellow and his colleagues in June 2014.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In a GAN, two neural networks compete with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one agent's gain is another agent's loss.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Given a training set, this technique learns to generate new data with the same statistics as the training set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on photographs can generate new photographs that look at least superficially authentic to human observers, having many realistic characteristics.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Though originally proposed as a form of generative model for unsupervised learning, GANs have also proved useful for semi-supervised learning, fully supervised learning, and reinforcement learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The core idea of a GAN is based on the "indirect" training through the discriminator, another neural network that can tell how "realistic" the input seems, which itself is also being updated dynamically.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This means that the generator is not trained to minimize the distance to a specific image, but rather to fool the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This enables the model to learn in an unsupervised manner.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are similar to mimicry in evolutionary biology, with an evolutionary arms race between both networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator's task is to approach $\mu _{G}\approx \mu _{\text{ref}}$ , that is, to match its own output distribution as closely as possible to the reference distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's task is to output a value close to 1 when the input appears to be from the reference distribution, and to output a value close to 0 when the input looks like it came from the generator distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The *generative* network generates candidates while the *discriminative* network evaluates them.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This creates a contest based on data distributions, where the generator learns to map from a latent space to the true data distribution, aiming to produce candidates that the discriminator cannot distinguish from real data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's goal is to correctly identify these candidates, but as the generator improves, its task becomes more challenging, increasing the discriminator's error rate.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A known dataset serves as the initial training data for the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Training involves presenting it with samples from the training dataset until it achieves acceptable accuracy.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator is trained based on whether it succeeds in fooling the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Typically, the generator is seeded with randomized input that is sampled from a predefined latent space (e.g. a multivariate normal distribution).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Thereafter, candidates synthesized by the generator are evaluated by the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Independent backpropagation procedures are applied to both networks so that the generator produces better samples, while the discriminator becomes more skilled at flagging synthetic samples.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When used for image generation, the generator is typically a deconvolutional neural network, and the discriminator is a convolutional neural network.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are **implicit generative models**, which means that they do not explicitly model the likelihood function nor provide a means for finding the latent variable corresponding to a given sample, unlike alternatives such as flow-based generative model.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to fully visible belief networks such as WaveNet and PixelRNN and autoregressive models in general, GANs can generate one complete sample in one pass, rather than multiple passes through the network.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to Boltzmann machines and linear ICA, there is no restriction on the type of function used by the network.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since neural networks are universal approximators, GANs are asymptotically consistent.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Variational autoencoders might be universal approximators, but it is not proven as of 2017.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This section provides some of the mathematical theory behind these methods.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In modern probability theory based on measure theory, a probability space also needs to be equipped with a σ-algebra.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since issues of measurability never arise in practice, these will not concern us further.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the most generic version of the GAN game described above, the strategy set for the discriminator contains all Markov kernels $\mu _{D}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}[0,1]$ , and the strategy set for the generator contains arbitrary probability distributions $\mu _{G}$ on $\Omega$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, as shown below, the optimal discriminator strategy against any $\mu _{G}$ is deterministic, so there is no loss of generality in restricting the discriminator's strategies to deterministic functions $D:\Omega \to [0,1]$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In most applications, D is a deep neural network function.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As for the generator, while $\mu _{G}$ could theoretically be any computable probability distribution, in practice, it is usually implemented as a pushforward: $\mu _{G}=\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, start with a random variable $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ , where $\mu _{Z}$ is a probability distribution that is easy to compute (such as the uniform distribution, or the Gaussian distribution), then define a function $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then the distribution $\mu _{G}$ is the distribution of $G(z)$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Consequently, the generator's strategy is usually defined as just G , leaving $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ implicit.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture has two main components.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One is casting optimization into a game, of form $\min _{G}\max _{D}L(G,D)$ , which is different from the usual kind of optimization, of form $\min _{\theta }L(\theta )$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The other is the decomposition of $\mu _{G}$ into $\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ , which can be understood as a reparametrization trick.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To see its significance, one must compare GAN with previous methods for learning generative models, which were plagued with "intractable probabilistic computations that arise in maximum likelihood estimation and related strategies".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] At the same time, Kingma and Welling and Rezende et al. developed the same idea of reparametrization into a general stochastic backpropagation method.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Among its first applications was the variational autoencoder.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] If both the generator's and the discriminator's strategy sets are spanned by a finite number of strategies, then by the minimax theorem, $\min _{\mu _{G}}\max _{\mu _{D}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})=\max _{\mu _{D}}\min _{\mu _{G}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})$ that is, the move order does not matter.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, since the strategy sets are both not finitely spanned, the minimax theorem does not apply, and the idea of an "equilibrium" becomes delicate.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For general games, these equilibria do not have to agree, or even to exist.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For the original GAN game, these equilibria all exist, and are all equal.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, for more general GAN games, these do not necessarily exist, or agree.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] where the derivative is the Radon–Nikodym derivative, and $D_{JS}$ is the Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The integrand is just the negative cross-entropy between two Bernoulli random variables with parameters $\rho _{\text{ref}}(x)$ and $D(x)$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, the generator perfectly mimics the reference, and the discriminator outputs ${\frac {1}{2}}$ deterministically on all inputs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] By Jensen's inequality, the discriminator can only improve by adopting the deterministic strategy of always playing $D(x)=\operatorname {E} _{y\sim \mu _{D}(x)}[y]$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When $\forall x\in \Omega ,\mu _{D}(x)=\delta _{\frac {1}{2}}$ , any strategy is optimal for the generator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] While the GAN game has a unique global equilibrium point when both the generator and discriminator have access to their entire strategy sets, the equilibrium is no longer guaranteed when they have a restricted strategy set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In practice, the generator has access only to measures of form $\mu _{Z}\circ G_{\theta }^{-1}$ , where $G_{\theta }$ is a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\theta$ , and $\mu _{Z}$ is an easily sampled distribution, such as the uniform or normal distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Similarly, the discriminator has access only to functions of form $D_{\zeta }$ , a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\zeta$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] These restricted strategy sets take up a *vanishingly small proportion* of their entire strategy sets.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Further, even if an equilibrium still exists, it can only be found by searching in the high-dimensional space of all possible neural network functions.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard strategy of using gradient descent to find the equilibrium often does not work for GAN, and often the game "collapses" into one of several failure modes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To improve the convergence stability, some training strategies start with an easier task, such as generating low-resolution images or simple images (one object with uniform background), and gradually increase the difficulty of the task during training.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This essentially translates to applying a curriculum learning scheme.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs often suffer from **mode collapse** where they fail to generalize properly, missing entire modes from the input data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on the MNIST dataset containing many samples of each digit might only generate pictures of digit 0.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was termed "the Helvetica scenario".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A typical mechanism for mode collapse is the generator only generating one or a few of the likely values, or a very incomplete picture of the target distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As the discriminator is only trained to distinguish real from fake samples, it will correctly identify the generated samples as real, but no penalty is imposed on the GAN's ability to generate data that represents the full range of the target distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Weak discriminators, for instance underparametrized ones, or ones trained too slow compared to the generator, may as well be unable to fully discriminate over the entire support of the distribution, and only become able to correctly discriminate a very incomplete part of the target distribution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Some researchers perceive the root problem to be a weak discriminative network that fails to notice the pattern of omission, while others assign blame to a bad choice of objective function.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many solutions have been proposed, but it is still an open problem.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Even the state-of-the-art architecture, BigGAN (2019), could not avoid mode collapse.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors resorted to "allowing collapse to occur at the later stages of training, by which time a model is sufficiently trained to achieve good results".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The **two time-scale update rule (TTUR)** is proposed to make GAN convergence more stable by making the learning rate of the generator lower than that of the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They prove that when trained this way, GANs "converge, under mild assumptions to a stationary local Nash equilibrium".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further show that this property extends to the use of the Adam optimizer, which is commonly used in stochastic gradient descent.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A local Nash equilibrium in no way signifies an absence of mode collapse - for instance, a GAN trained on MNIST collapsed to generating a single digit may satisfy the hypotheses of the paper, while still presenting mode collapse.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conversely, if the discriminator learns too fast compared to the generator, then the discriminator could almost perfectly distinguish $\mu _{G_{\theta }},\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator $G_{\theta }$ could be stuck with a very high loss no matter which direction it changes its $\theta$ , meaning that the gradient $\nabla _{\theta }L(G_{\theta },D_{\zeta })$ would be close to zero.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator cannot learn, a case of the **vanishing gradient** problem.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Intuitively speaking, the discriminator is too good, and since the generator cannot take any small step (only small steps are considered in gradient descent) to improve its payoff, it does not even try.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One important method for solving this problem is the Wasserstein GAN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many papers that propose new GAN architectures for image generation report how their architectures break the state of the art on FID or IS.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The model is finetuned so that it can approximate $\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|\approx \operatorname {perceptual~difference} (x,x')$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This finetuned model is then used to define $\operatorname {LPIPS} (x,x'):=\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other evaluation methods are reviewed in.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] There is a veritable zoo of GAN variants.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conditional GANs are similar to standard GANs except they allow the model to conditionally generate samples based on additional information.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, if we want to generate a cat face given a dog picture, we could use a conditional GAN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator in a GAN game generates $\mu _{G}$ , a probability distribution on the probability space $\Omega$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This leads to the idea of a conditional GAN, where instead of generating one probability distribution on $\Omega$ , the generator generates a different probability distribution $\mu _{G}(c)$ on $\Omega$ , for each given class label c .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, for generating images that look like ImageNet, the generator should be able to generate a picture of cat when given the class label "cat".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors noted that GAN can be trivially extended to conditional GAN by providing the labels to both the generator and the discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In 2017, a conditional GAN learned to generate 1000 image classes of ImageNet.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN game is a general framework and can be run with any reasonable parametrization of the generator G and discriminator D .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors demonstrated it using multilayer perceptron networks and convolutional neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many alternative architectures have been tried.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many GAN variants are merely obtained by changing the loss functions for the generator and discriminator.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This objective for generator was recommended in the original paper for faster convergence. $L_{G}=\operatorname {E} _{x\sim \mu _{G}}[\ln D(x)]$ The effect of using this objective is analyzed in Section 2.2.2 of Arjovsky et al.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the discriminator is optimal, the generator gradient is the same as in maximum likelihood estimation, even though GAN cannot perform maximum likelihood estimation *itself*.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One of its purposes is to solve the problem of mode collapse (see above).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors claim "In no experiment did we see evidence of mode collapse for the WGAN algorithm".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] An adversarial autoencoder (AAE) is more autoencoder than GAN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The idea is to start with a plain autoencoder, but train a discriminator to discriminate the latent vectors from a reference distribution (often the normal distribution).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In conditional GAN, the generator receives both a noise vector z and a label c , and produces an image $G(z,c)$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator receives image-label pairs $(x,c)$ , and computes $D(x,c)$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the training dataset is unlabeled, conditional GAN does not work directly.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard GAN generator is a function of type $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega _{X}$ , that is, it is a mapping from a latent space $\Omega _{Z}$ to the image space $\Omega _{X}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This can be understood as a "decoding" process, whereby every latent vector $z\in \Omega _{Z}$ is a code for an image $x\in \Omega _{X}$ , and the generator performs the decoding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This naturally leads to the idea of training another network that performs "encoding", creating an autoencoder out of the encoder-generator pair.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Already in the original paper, the authors noted that "Learned approximate inference can be performed by training an auxiliary network to predict z given x ".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The bidirectional GAN architecture performs exactly this.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Applications of bidirectional models include semi-supervised learning, interpretable machine learning, and neural machine translation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] CycleGAN is an architecture for performing translations between two domains, such as between photos of horses and photos of zebras, or photos of night cities and photos of day cities.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Unlike previous work like pix2pix, which requires paired training data, cycleGAN requires no paired data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The BigGAN is essentially a self-attention GAN trained on a large scale (up to 80 million parameters) to generate large images of ImageNet (up to 512 x 512 resolution), with numerous engineering tricks to make it converge.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When there is insufficient training data, the reference distribution $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ cannot be well-approximated by the empirical distribution given by the training dataset.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such cases, data augmentation can be applied, to allow training GAN on smaller datasets.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Naïve data augmentation, however, brings its problems.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The result of such training would be a generator that mimics $\mu _{\text{ref}}'$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, it would generate images that look like they are randomly cropped, if the data augmentation uses random cropping.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN-2-ADA paper points out a further point on data augmentation: it must be *invertible*.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Continue with the example of generating ImageNet pictures.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They would have exactly the same expected loss, and so neither is preferred over the other.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The solution is to only use invertible data augmentation: instead of "randomly rotate the picture by 0, 90, 180, 270 degrees with *equal* probability", use "randomly rotate the picture by 90, 180, 270 degrees with 0.1 probability, and keep the picture as it is with 0.7 probability".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This way, the generator is still rewarded to keep images oriented the same way as un-augmented ImageNet pictures.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Abstractly, the effect of randomly sampling transformations $T:\Omega \to \Omega$ from the distribution $\mu _{\text{trans}}$ is to define a Markov kernel $K_{\text{trans}}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, the data-augmented GAN game pushes the generator to find some ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}\in {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ , such that $K_{\text{trans}}*\mu _{\text{ref}}=K_{\text{trans}}*{\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ where * is the Markov kernel convolution.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Also by definition, if the data-augmentation method is invertible, then using it in a GAN game does not change the optimal strategy ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ for the generator, which is still $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] With that, we can recover $\mu$ by running the heat equation *backwards in time* for $\epsilon ^{2}/4$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] More examples of invertible data augmentations are found in the paper.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] SinGAN pushes data augmentation to the limit, by using only a single image as training data and performing data augmentation on it.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture is adapted to this training method by using a multi-scale pipeline.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator is decomposed into a pyramid as well.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN family is a series of architectures published by Nvidia's research division.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Progressive GAN is a method for training GAN for large-scale image generation stably, by growing a GAN generator from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Like SinGAN, it decomposes the generator as $G=G_{1}\circ G_{2}\circ \cdots \circ G_{N}$ , and the discriminator as $D=D_{1}\circ D_{2}\circ \cdots \circ D_{N}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] During training, at first only $G_{N},D_{N}$ are used in a GAN game to generate 4x4 images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then $G_{N-1},D_{N-1}$ are added to reach the second stage of GAN game, to generate 8x8 images, and so on, until we reach a GAN game to generate 1024x1024 images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To avoid shock between stages of the GAN game, each new layer is "blended in" (Figure 2 of the paper).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-1 is designed as a combination of Progressive GAN with neural style transfer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The key architectural choice of StyleGAN-1 is a progressive growth mechanism, similar to Progressive GAN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each generated image starts as a constant $4\times 4\times 512$ array, and repeatedly passed through style blocks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each style block applies a "style latent vector" via affine transform ("adaptive instance normalization"), similar to how neural style transfer uses Gramian matrix.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It then adds noise, and normalize (subtract the mean, then divide by the variance).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] After training, multiple style latent vectors can be fed into each style block.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Those fed to the lower layers control the large-scale styles, and those fed to the higher layers control the fine-detail styles.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Style-mixing between two images $x,x'$ can be performed as well.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] First, run a gradient descent to find $z,z'$ such that $G(z)\approx x,G(z')\approx x'$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This is called "projecting an image back to style latent space".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, z can be fed to the lower style blocks, and $z'$ to the higher style blocks, to generate a composite image that has the large-scale style of x , and the fine-detail style of $x'$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Multiple images can also be composed this way.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-2 improves upon StyleGAN-1, by using the style latent vector to transform the convolution layer's weights instead, thus solving the "blob" problem.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was updated by the StyleGAN-2-ADA ("ADA" stands for "adaptive"), which uses invertible data augmentation as described above.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It also tunes the amount of data augmentation applied by starting at zero, and gradually increasing it until an "overfitting heuristic" reaches a target level, thus the name "adaptive".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-3 improves upon StyleGAN-2 by solving the "texture sticking" problem, which can be seen in the official videos.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They analyzed the problem by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, and argued that the layers in the generator learned to exploit the high-frequency signal in the pixels they operate upon.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To solve this, they proposed imposing strict lowpass filters between each generator's layers, so that the generator is forced to operate on the pixels in a way faithful to the continuous signals they represent, rather than operate on them as merely discrete signals.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further imposed rotational and translational invariance by using more signal filters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting StyleGAN-3 is able to solve the texture sticking problem, as well as generating images that rotate and translate smoothly.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other than for generative and discriminative modelling of data, GANs have been used for other things.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs have been used for transfer learning to enforce the alignment of the latent feature space, such as in deep reinforcement learning.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This works by feeding the embeddings of the source and target task to the discriminator which tries to guess the context.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting loss is then (inversely) backpropagated through the encoder.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN-generated molecules were validated experimentally in mice.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] One of the major concerns in medical imaging is preserving patient privacy.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Due to these reasons, researchers often face difficulties in obtaining medical images for their research purposes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN has been used for generating synthetic medical images, such as MRI and PET images to address this challenge.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN can be used to detect glaucomatous images helping the early diagnosis which is essential to avoid partial or total loss of vision.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs have been used to create forensic facial reconstructions of deceased historical figures.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Concerns have been raised about the potential use of GAN-based human image synthesis for sinister purposes, e.g., to produce fake, possibly incriminating, photographs and videos.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be used to generate unique, realistic profile photos of people who do not exist, in order to automate creation of fake social media profiles.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Both bills were authored by Assembly member Marc Berman and signed by Governor Gavin Newsom.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] DARPA's Media Forensics program studies ways to counteract fake media, including fake media produced using GANs.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Some have worked with using GAN for artistic creativity, as "creative adversarial network".
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] A GAN, trained on a set of 15,000 portraits from WikiArt from the 14th to the 19th century, created the 2018 painting *Edmond de Belamy,* which sold for US$432,500.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs were used by the video game modding community to up-scale low-resolution 2D textures in old video games by recreating them in 4k or higher resolutions via image training, and then down-sampling them to fit the game's native resolution (resembling supersampling anti-aliasing).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2020, Artbreeder was used to create the main antagonist in the sequel to the psychological web horror series *Ben Drowned*.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The author would later go on to praise GAN applications for their ability to help generate assets for independent artists who are short on budget and manpower.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In May 2020, Nvidia researchers taught an AI system (termed "GameGAN") to recreate the game of *Pac-Man* simply by watching it being played.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In August 2019, a large dataset consisting of 12,197 MIDI songs each with paired lyrics and melody alignment was created for neural melody generation from lyrics using conditional GAN-LSTM (refer to sources at GitHub AI Melody Generation from Lyrics).
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 1991, Juergen Schmidhuber published "artificial curiosity", neural networks in a zero-sum game.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be regarded as a case where the environmental reaction is 1 or 0 depending on whether the first network's output is in a given set.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Other people had similar ideas but did not develop them similarly.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea involving adversarial networks was published in a 2010 blog post by Olli Niemitalo.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] This idea was never implemented and did not involve stochasticity in the generator and thus was not a generative model.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea similar to GANs was used to model animal behavior by Wei Li, Melvin Gauci and Roderich Gross in 2013.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Another inspiration for GANs was noise-contrastive estimation, which uses the same loss function as GANs and which Goodfellow studied during his PhD in 2010–2014.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Adversarial machine learning has other uses besides generative modeling and can be applied to models other than neural networks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In control theory, adversarial learning based on neural networks was used in 2006 to train robust controllers in a game theoretic sense, by alternating the iterations between a minimizer policy, the controller, and a maximizer policy, the disturbance.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, a GAN was used for image enhancement focusing on realistic textures rather than pixel-accuracy, producing a higher image quality at high magnification.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, the first faces were generated.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] These were exhibited in February 2018 at the Grand Palais.
[src:style-transfer-cv/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Faces generated by StyleGAN in 2019 drew comparisons with Deepfakes.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] A **latent space**, also known as a **latent feature space** or **embedding space**, is an embedding of a set of items within a manifold in which items resembling each other are positioned closer to one another.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Position within the latent space can be viewed as being defined by a set of latent variables that emerge from the resemblances between the objects.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] In most cases, the dimensionality of the latent space is chosen to be lower than the dimensionality of the feature space from which the data points are drawn, making the construction of a latent space an example of dimensionality reduction, which can also be viewed as a form of data compression.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Latent spaces are usually fit via machine learning, and they can then be used as feature spaces in machine learning models, including classifiers and other supervised predictors.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] The interpretation of latent spaces in machine learning models is an ongoing area of research, but achieving clear interpretations remains challenging.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] The black-box nature of these models often makes the latent space unintuitive, while its high-dimensional, complex, and nonlinear characteristics further complicate the task of understanding it.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Analysis of the latent space geometry of diffusion models reveals a fractal structure of phase transitions in the latent space, characterized by abrupt changes in the Fisher information metric.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Some visualization techniques have been developed to connect the latent space to the visual world, but there is often not a direct connection between the latent space interpretation and the model itself.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Such techniques include t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE), where the latent space is mapped to two dimensions for visualization.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Latent space distances lack physical units, so the interpretation of these distances may depend on the application.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Several embedding models have been developed to perform this transformation to create latent space embeddings given a set of data items and a similarity function.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] These models learn the embeddings by leveraging statistical techniques and machine learning algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] GloVe: GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) is another widely used embedding model for NLP.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] It combines global statistical information from a corpus with local context information to learn word embeddings.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] GloVe embeddings are known for capturing both semantic and relational similarities between words.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Siamese Networks: Siamese networks are a type of neural network architecture commonly used for similarity-based embedding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] They consist of two identical subnetworks that process two input samples and produce their respective embeddings.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Siamese networks are often used for tasks like image similarity, recommendation systems, and face recognition.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Variational Autoencoders (VAEs): VAEs are generative models that simultaneously learn to encode and decode data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] The latent space in VAEs acts as an embedding space.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] By training VAEs on high-dimensional data, such as images or audio, the model learns to encode the data into a compact latent representation.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] VAEs are known for their ability to generate new data samples from the learned latent space.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Multimodality refers to the integration and analysis of multiple modes or types of data within a single model or framework.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Embedding multimodal data involves capturing relationships and interactions between different data types, such as images, text, audio, and structured data.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] Multimodal embedding models aim to learn joint representations that fuse information from multiple modalities, allowing for cross-modal analysis and tasks.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] These models enable applications like image captioning, visual question answering, and multimodal sentiment analysis.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] To embed multimodal data, specialized architectures such as deep multimodal networks or multimodal transformers are employed.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] These architectures combine different types of neural network modules to process and integrate information from various modalities.
[src:style-transfer-cv/latent-space] The resulting embeddings capture the complex relationships between different data types, facilitating multimodal analysis and understanding.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] NST is an example of image stylization, a problem studied for over two decades within the field of non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The first two example-based style transfer algorithms were image analogies and image quilting.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Both of these methods were based on patch-based texture synthesis algorithms.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Given a training pair of images–a photo and an artwork depicting that photo–a transformation could be learned and then applied to create new artwork from a new photo, by analogy.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] If no training photo was available, it would need to be produced by processing the input artwork; image quilting did not require this processing step, though it was demonstrated on only one style.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] NST was first published in the paper "A Neural Algorithm of Artistic Style" by Leon Gatys et al., originally released to ArXiv 2015, and subsequently accepted by the peer-reviewed CVPR conference in 2016.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The original paper used a VGG-19 architecture that has been pre-trained to perform object recognition using the ImageNet dataset.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] In 2017, Google AI introduced a method that allows a single deep convolutional style transfer network to learn multiple styles at the same time.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] This algorithm permits style interpolation in real-time, even when done on video media.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] This section closely follows the original paper.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Both the content loss and the style loss measures the similarity of two images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The content similarity is the weighted sum of squared-differences between the neural activations of a single convolutional neural network (CNN) on two images.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The style similarity is the weighted sum of Gram matrices within each layer (see below for details).
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The original paper used a VGG-19 CNN, but the method works for any CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Let ${\textstyle {\vec {x}}}$ be an image input to a CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] A given input image ${\textstyle {\vec {x}}}$ is encoded in each layer of the CNN by the filter responses to that image, with higher layers encoding more global features, but losing details on local features.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Let ${\textstyle {\vec {p}}}$ be an original image.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Let ${\textstyle {\vec {x}}}$ be an image that is generated to match the content of ${\textstyle {\vec {p}}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Let ${\textstyle P^{l}}$ be the matrix of filter responses in layer ${\textstyle l}$ to the image ${\textstyle {\vec {p}}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Minimizing this loss encourages the generated image to have similar content to the content image, as captured by the feature activations in the chosen layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The total content loss is a linear sum of the content losses of each layer: ${\mathcal {L}}_{\text{content }}({\vec {p}},{\vec {x}})=\sum _{l}v_{l}{\mathcal {L}}_{\text{content }}({\vec {p}},{\vec {x}},l)$ , where the $v_{l}$ are positive real numbers chosen as hyperparameters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Minimizing this loss encourages the generated image to have similar style characteristics to the style image, as captured by the correlations between feature responses in each layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The idea is that activation pattern correlations between filters in a single layer captures the "style" on the order of the receptive fields at that layer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Similarly to the previous case, the $w_{l}$ are positive real numbers chosen as hyperparameters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] In the original paper, they used a particular choice of hyperparameters.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The style loss is computed by $w_{l}=0.2$ for the outputs of layers `conv1_1`, `conv2_1`, `conv3_1`, `conv4_1`, `conv5_1` in the VGG-19 network, and zero otherwise.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] The content loss is computed by $w_{l}=1$ for `conv4_2`, and zero otherwise.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Image ${\vec {x}}$ is initially approximated by adding a small amount of white noise to input image ${\vec {p}}$ and feeding it through the CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Then we successively backpropagate this loss through the network with the CNN weights fixed in order to update the pixels of ${\vec {x}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] After several thousand epochs of training, an ${\vec {x}}$ (hopefully) emerges that matches the style of ${\vec {a}}$ and the content of ${\vec {p}}$ .
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] As of 2017, when implemented on a GPU, it takes a few minutes to converge.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] In some practical implementations, it is noted that the resulting image has too much high-frequency artifact, which can be suppressed by adding the total variation to the total loss.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Compared to VGGNet, AlexNet does not work well for neural style transfer.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Subsequent work improved the speed of NST for images by using special-purpose normalizations.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] In a paper by Fei-Fei Li et al. adopted a different regularized loss metric and accelerated method for training to produce results in real-time (three orders of magnitude faster than Gatys).
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Their idea was to use not the *pixel-based loss* defined above but rather a 'perceptual loss' measuring the differences between higher-level layers within the CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] They used a symmetric convolution-deconvolution CNN.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Training uses a similar loss function to the basic NST method but also regularizes the output for smoothness using a total variation (TV) loss.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Once trained, the network may be used to transform an image into the style used during training, using a single feed-forward pass of the network.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] However the network is restricted to the single style in which it has been trained.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] In a work by Chen Dongdong et al. they explored the fusion of optical flow information into feedforward networks in order to improve the temporal coherence of the output.
[src:style-transfer-cv/neural-style-transfer] Most recently, feature transform based NST methods have been explored for fast stylization that are not coupled to single specific style and enable user-controllable *blending* of styles, for example the whitening and coloring transform (WCT).
